<br>
Verant mentioned early on that twitch combat systems wouldnt work well on MMORPGs, and I think we all agree.<br>
<br>
On the flip side , waiting 51 lvls before you get any sort of /disciplin isnt ideal either when the rest of the time you hit autoattack and watch your swings, you watch your double attack and dual wield and every now and then bash or kick or backstab or flying kick or whathave you.  But most of the time you are watching that attacks and spending the majority of the energy watching your health bar, the mobshealth bar, and chasing around the mob taunting it, trying to avoid the &quot;you cannont see your target from here&quot; message that has plagued you since lvl 1.<br>
<br>
At the time it seemed like a decent system, crits were added, crips were added, dmg bonus was tweaked but the mainstay of the system was you hit autoattack, and watch your guy take the same swings over and over again.  More joy is gotten out of reading the logs of hits than the actual combat itself.  I know I have read logs of battles and been pretty interested, in fact watching your own battle spam is often more entertaining than anything else going on besides the occasional gravity flux.<br>
<br>
Well what could be better? especially if you elminate twitch?<br>
<br>
1. Animations - even if EQs combat system remained the same, adding animations for swings would make things tons more interesting.  Take a look at some of the shadowbane animations for combat, while the elf dual wielding looks a little bit like a faerie it is certainly more interesting than your typical overhand swing in EQ.<br>
<br>
2. &quot;Z&quot; targeting.  Having the ability to lock onto a target ala Zelda 64 is a huge bonus.  While in EQ you can lock on sort of, a number of things can go wrong, not to mention the blinking name above the NPCs head isnt exactly the deal sealer when targetting, nor is the NPC name in the window.  I think most MMORPGs coming out are going to have a more straight forward targetting system<br>
<br>
3. Body parts- in EQ snare is the be all and end all spell for a lot of levels in a lot of zones. There is no other way to slow a mob other than magic snare type spells or to bring it to like 15% health.  Hitting something in the knee caps just never occured to them I guess.  Targetting a mobs legs should have a chance to slow it if you do hit it enough.  Imagine hitting an ogre in the knees with a mace 4-5 times, then running away and bow kiting it.  Or Troll gets tired of chasing an elf around and uses a whip to snap his achilles tendon and thus slowing him?  <br>
<br>
Or hacking away at someone's arm thus slowing their attack speed.  Or head shots being harder to get but having a greater chance to stun?<br>
<br>
These are not new ideas, many RPGs and action games have this type of thing, Vagrant Story ( i happen to be playing currently) uses some of these.<br>
<br>
When you look at EQ melee is basically like chopping down a tree.  You hack away at something, it hacks away at you.  The cleric heals you, you continue to hack, eventually the mob gets low on health, turns and runs, then dies.<br>
<br>
You never hear more cheers from a warrior then if his snare whip goes off, or if he slows the mob or something.  its the magic system in EQ that is really the fun part, so much so that all classes now have magic (they demanded it) from pure melee to wizzards, everyone is tossing around spells left and right.  Its basically &quot;magicquest&quot; the game is to try and get magic items like armour and weapons that have magic effects , like cobalt breasplates, and bloodpoints.<br>
<br>
THe next MMORPGs hopefully will implement some of these ideas and more to make melee as interesting as magic, make both viable forms of combat.  EQ is basically healing is trivial at the early levels, and is the be all end all at high lvls.  Melee dmg is peanuts compared to caster dmg at low lvls, then suddenly at high lvls mobs resist all magic, or the really fun magic like snares.<br>
<br>
Combat types should have their pros and cons,  like attacking a leg might work really well for some mobs, but be futile for others, ghosts for example, attacking their legs shouldnt have any affect, yet chopping off a minotaurs leg might substantially slow it down.<br>
<br>
Hacking a hand off a human could reduce his effectiveness by like 40%, but hacking a tentacle off a TT does little good.<br>
<br>
Dont you think that would be much more fun than &quot;slashing a fire imp for 80 pts dmg&quot; and thinking &quot; ok only 278 more swings to go before I chop down this tree <p><b>Saevan Expane
